      "content": "The \"vanishing\" units are a classic symptom of a problem that's harder to solve than it looks. In this case, you might want to consider implementing a \"suspicious activity\" tracking system, where you can monitor and record any unusual transactions or movements of inventory. This can help you identify patterns or anomalies that might indicate theft or other forms of shrinkage.\n\nYou can also consider using \"time-stamped\" inventory tracking, where you can record the exact time and location of any inventory movements. This can help you identify any gaps in the record and pinpoint the exact time when the units went missing.\n\nAnother approach is to use \" RFID\" (Radio Frequency Identification) tags, which can be attached to individual units of inventory and track their movements in real-time. This can provide a more detailed and accurate picture of where the units are and when they're being moved.\n\nIt's also worth considering implementing a \"inventory rotation\" process, where you regularly rotate and re-label inventory to prevent it from becoming \"stale\" or outdated. This can help reduce the risk of inventory becoming obsolete or being \"lost\" in the system.\n\nBy combining these approaches, you can create a more robust and effective system for tracking and preventing shrinkage. And",
